 <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 pt-10 sm:px-6 lg:px-8"><img src={post.image} alt="Welder in NFPA 2112 FR shirt and leather welding jacket on a Las Vegas job site" width="1200" height="675" loading="eager" class="w-full border border-hairline object-cover" /></div>
 <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">

 <aside class="mb-10 border border-hairline bg-panel p-7">
 <p class="mb-3 font-mono text-[10px] font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-700">Quick Answer</p>
 <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal sm:text-xl">A welder uniform in Las Vegas is a layered system: NFPA 2112 FR base shirt and pants, leather welding jacket or sleeves over the FR, leather gloves, welding helmet, and steel-toe boots. OSHA 1910.252 and AWS Z49.1 require FR. Decorate FR garments with Nomex embroidery thread, never plastisol screen print.</p>
 </aside>

 <h2 id="layered-system" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-charcoal">The Welder Uniform Is a Layered System</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Most "welder uniform" search results stop at FR shirts. That misses the point. A real welder uniform is three protective layers, each handling a different hazard:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>Layer 1 — FR base.</strong> Long-sleeve NFPA 2112 shirt and pants. Self-extinguishes if ignition happens. Required by OSHA.</li>
 <li><strong>Layer 2 — Leather over-layer.</strong> Split-cowhide jacket or sleeves. Deflects direct slag and arc spatter the FR base wasn\'t designed to take head-on.</li>
 <li><strong>Layer 3 — Head, hands, feet.</strong> Welding helmet with FR balaclava or skullcap, gauntlet leather gloves, and steel-toe boots with metatarsal guard.</li>
 </ul>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Authoritative sources: <a href="https://www.osha.gov/laws-regs/regulations/standardnumber/1910/1910.252" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600" rel="noopener" target="_blank">OSHA 29 CFR 1910.252</a> on welding PPE, and <a href="https://www.aws.org/standards" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600" rel="noopener" target="_blank">AWS Z49.1 Safety in Welding, Cutting, and Allied Processes</a>.</p>

 <h2 id="fr-base-layer" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-charcoal">FR Base Layer — Brand Picks for Vegas</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Vegas summer hits 110°F+. The FR shirt has to breathe or your welders won\'t wear it correctly. Sleeves get rolled up, shirts get unbuttoned, and the FR rating becomes theoretical.</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>Bulwark Excel-FR ComforTouch SLU2 (7 oz).</strong> Dual NFPA 70E + 2112 rating. Most-specified Vegas welder/electrician shirt.</li>
 <li><strong>Carhartt FR Force.</strong> Cotton/nylon blend, moisture-wicking. Solid mid-tier pick.</li>
 <li><strong>Lapco FR.</strong> Heavier 7-oz cotton. More durable for shop welding, hotter for outdoor.</li>
 <li><strong>Tyndale FR.</strong> Industrial-laundry favorite. Bulk-program friendly.</li>
 </ul>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">For deeper FR detail see <a href="/blog/welder-uniforms-fr-shirts-las-vegas/" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">our FR-specific welder shirt guide</a>, plus <a href="/blog/bulwark-fr-shirts-vegas-heat/" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">Bulwark FR shirts in Vegas heat</a> and <a href="/blog/nfpa-2112-fr-coveralls-buyer-guide/" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">NFPA 2112 FR coveralls</a>.</p>

 <h2 id="leather-over-layer" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-charcoal">Leather Over-Layer — Jackets vs Sleeves vs Bibs</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">The leather choice depends on the welding process and ambient heat:</p>
 <div class="my-6 overflow-x-auto border border-hairline bg-panel">
 <table class="w-full text-base text-charcoal">
 <thead class="bg-paper text-left text-xs font-mono uppercase tracking-wider text-gold-700">
 <tr><th class="px-5 py-3">Garment</th><th class="px-5 py-3">Best For</th></tr>
 </thead>
 <tbody class="divide-y divide-hairline">
 <tr><td class="px-5 py-3">Full split-cowhide jacket</td><td class="px-5 py-3">Stick / SMAW &gt; 200A, structural welding, overhead</td></tr>
 <tr><td class="px-5 py-3">Leather sleeves + bib</td><td class="px-5 py-3">MIG / TIG, hot Vegas summer, mobile welders</td></tr>
 <tr><td class="px-5 py-3">Leather sleeves only</td><td class="px-5 py-3">Light-duty TIG, fab shop bench work</td></tr>
 <tr><td class="px-5 py-3">FR jacket (no leather)</td><td class="px-5 py-3">Welding-adjacent trades, fitter, helper</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table>
 </div>

 <h2 id="branding-fr" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-charcoal">Branding FR Welder Uniforms Without Voiding the Rating</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">FR garments retain their NFPA 2112 certification only when decorated correctly. The rules:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>Use Nomex thread for embroidery.</strong> Standard polyester thread melts and drips — a burn hazard worse than no decoration. Nomex is FR-rated and approved by every major FR brand.</li>
 <li><strong>Avoid plastisol screen printing on FR.</strong> Cured plastisol ignites and adds fuel. Some FR brands tolerate water-based ink in small placements; most don\'t.</li>
 <li><strong>Keep decoration off the chest burn zone.</strong> Logo on the left chest is fine. Avoid large back prints over the spine and shoulder area.</li>
 <li><strong>Get your FR shop\'s decoration written confirmation.</strong> If the brand\'s decoration policy isn\'t in writing, the certification claim doesn\'t hold up.</li>
 </ul>

 <h2 id="rental-vs-owned" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-charcoal">Uniform Rental vs Owned Program</h2>
 <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Vegas welding shops pick between two models:</p>
 <ul class="mb-6 list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>Rental (Cintas, UniFirst, Aramark).</strong> Weekly delivery, laundry included, garments swapped on damage. Works at 30+ welders. Garments are shared, generic-fit, and FR rating depends on rental shop\'s laundering. Branding limited to standard patches.</li>
 <li><strong>Owned program with company store.</strong> Each welder has their own gear, sized correctly, embroidered with the company logo and name. More work upfront, better-fitting kit, fewer compliance questions. Works at any size — 5 welders to 500. See our take on <a href="/blog/company-store-vs-bulk-ordering/" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">company store vs bulk ordering</a>.</li>
 </ul>

 <h2 id="program-spec" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-charcoal">How to Spec a Welder Uniform Program</h2>
 <p class="mb-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">Full brand options and FR stock are on our <a href="/welder-uniforms-las-vegas/" class="text-gold-700 underline decoration-gold-500/40 underline-offset-4 hover:decoration-gold-600">welder uniforms Las Vegas</a> page. Standard program spec:</p>
 <ol class="mb-6 list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal">
 <li><strong>FR base.</strong> 5-7 long-sleeve shirts + 3-5 FR pants per welder. Bulwark or Carhartt FR for most Vegas crews.</li>
 <li><strong>Leather over-layer.</strong> One heavy jacket OR sleeves+bib per welder. Replace at split or burn-through.</li>
 <li><strong>Embroidery.</strong> Nomex thread, left chest logo, name on opposite chest if your shop differentiates roles.</li>
 <li><strong>Helmet & hood.</strong> Auto-darkening helmet (Lincoln, Miller, Optrel) with FR balaclava under it.</li>
 <li><strong>Boots & gloves.</strong> Steel-toe + metatarsal welding boots, gauntlet leather welding gloves (Tillman, Lincoln Electric).</li>
 </ol>

